<b>Leo Breiman</b> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../866/15866.xml">
January 27</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../674/34674.xml">
1928</link> â€“ <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../863/15863.xml">
July 7</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../984/35984.xml">
2005</link>) was a distinguished <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../661/48661.xml">
statistician</link> at the <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<ranking wordnetid="114429484" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../922/31922.xml">
University of California, Berkeley</link></ranking>
</university>
. He was the recipient of numerous honors and awards, and was a member of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../510/46510.xml">
 United States National Academy of Science</link>.<p>

Breiman's work bridged the gap between statisticians and computer scientists, particularly in the field of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../488/233488.xml">
machine learning</link>. Perhaps his most important contributions were his work on <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../602/232602.xml">
classification and regression trees</link> and ensembles of trees fit to <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../770/6885770.xml">
bootstrap</link> samples. <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../770/6885770.xml">
Bootstrap</link> aggregation was given the name <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../911/1307911.xml">
<it>bagging''</it></link> by Breiman. Another of Breiman's ensemble approaches is the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../880/1363880.xml">
random forest</link>.</p>

